# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-athena
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-athena/amazon-athena] Cloud analytics is designed to make official statistical data readily categorized and available via the users web browser.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-athena] The global Cloud Analytics Market size is expected to grow from USD 35.7 billion in 2024 to USD 118.5 billion in 2029, at a CAGR of 27.1% during the forecast period, according to a new report by MarketsandMarkets™.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-athena/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:aws-athena/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto was originally designed and developed at Facebook, Inc.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] (later renamed Meta) for their data analysts to run interactive queries on its large data warehouse in Apache Hadoop.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] The first four developers were Martin Traverso, Dain Sundstrom, David Phillips, and Eric Hwang.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Before Presto, the data analysts at Facebook relied on Apache Hive for running SQL analytics on their multi-petabyte data warehouse.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Hive was deemed too slow for Facebook's scale and Presto was invented to fill the gap to run fast queries.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Original development started in 2012 and deployed at Facebook later that year.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In November 2013, Facebook announced its open source release.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In 2014, Netflix disclosed they used Presto on 10 petabytes of data stored in the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3).
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In November, 2016, Amazon announced a service called Athena that was based on Presto.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In 2017, Teradata spun out a company called Starburst Data to commercially support Presto, which included staff acquired from Hadapt in 2014.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Teradata's QueryGrid software allowed Presto to access a Teradata relational database.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In January 2019, the Presto Software Foundation was announced.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] The foundation is a not-for-profit organization for the advancement of the Presto open source distributed SQL query engine.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] At the same time, Presto development forked: PrestoDB maintained by Facebook, and PrestoSQL maintained by the Presto Software Foundation, with some cross pollination of code.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In September 2019, Facebook donated PrestoDB to the Linux Foundation, establishing the Presto Foundation.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Neither the creators of Presto, nor the top contributors and committers, were invited to join this foundation.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] By 2020, all four of the original Presto developers had joined Starburst.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] In December 2020, PrestoSQL was rebranded as Trino, since Facebook had obtained a trademark on the name "Presto" (also donated to the Linux Foundation).
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Another company called Ahana was announced in 2020 to commercialize the PrestoDB fork as a cloud service and was acquired by IBM in 2023.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto's architecture is very similar to other database management systems using cluster computing, sometimes called massively parallel processing (MPP).
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] One coordinator works in sync with multiple workers.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Clients submit SQL statements that are parsed and planned, following which parallel tasks are scheduled to workers.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Workers jointly process rows from the data sources and produce results that are returned to the client.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Compared to the original Apache Hive execution model which used the Hadoop MapReduce mechanism on each query, Presto does not write intermediate results to disk, resulting in a significant speed improvement.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] A Presto query can combine data from multiple sources.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto offers connectors to data sources including files in Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (often called a data lake), Amazon S3, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Amazon Redshift, Apache Kudu, Apache Phoenix, Apache Kafka, Apache Cassandra, Apache Accumulo, MongoDB and Redis.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Unlike other Hadoop distribution-specific tools, such as Apache Impala, Presto can work with any variant of Hadoop or without it.
[src:aws-athena/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto supports separation of compute and storage and may be deployed on-premises or using cloud computing.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:aws-athena/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:aws-athena/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:aws-athena/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:aws-athena/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:aws-athena/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:aws-athena/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:aws-athena/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:aws-athena/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:aws-athena/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:aws-athena/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:aws-athena/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:aws-athena/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:aws-athena/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:aws-athena/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:aws-athena/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:aws-athena/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:aws-athena/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:aws-athena/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:aws-athena/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:aws-athena/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:aws-athena/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:aws-athena/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:aws-athena/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:aws-athena/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:aws-athena/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:aws-athena/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:aws-athena/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:aws-athena/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:aws-athena/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] In January 2019, the original creators of Presto, Martin Traverso, Dain Sundstrom, and David Phillips, created a fork of the Presto project.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] They initially kept the name Presto and used the PrestoSQL web handle to distinguish it from the original PrestoDB project.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Simultaneously, they announced the Presto Software Foundation.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] The foundation is a not-for-profit organization dedicated to the advancement of the Presto open source distributed SQL query engine.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] In December 2020, PrestoSQL was rebranded as Trino.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] The Trino Software Foundation, code base, and all other PrestoSQL assets were renamed as part of the rebrand.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Presto and Trino were originally designed and developed by Martin, Dain, David, and Eric Hwang at Facebook to allow data analysts to run interactive queries on its large data warehouse in Apache Hadoop.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino shares the first six years of development with the Presto project.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] To learn more about the earlier history of Trino, you can reference the Presto history section.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino is used in many data platforms and products from cloud providers and other vendors.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Customization of these products varies from pure Trino usage to heavily customized systems to run a data platform or integration in specialized data platforms for usage with specific data.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Examples include Amazon Athena, Starburst Galaxy, Dune, and many others.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] It runs on a cluster of servers that contains two types of nodes, a **coordinator** and a **worker**.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino adheres to the ANSI SQL standard and includes various parts of the following ANSI specifications: SQL-92, SQL:1999, SQL:2003, SQL:2008, SQL:2011, SQL:2016, SQL:2023.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino supports the separation of compute and storage and may be deployed both on-premises and in the cloud.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino has a Distributed computing MPP architecture.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino first distributes work over multiple workers by running ad-hoc partitioning operations or relying on existing partitions in the data of the underlying data store.
[src:aws-athena/trino-sql-query-engine] Once this data has reached the worker, the data is processed over pipelined operators carried out on multiple threads.
